Employees at this location seem to lack basic standards of customer service skills. Very rude, passive aggressive, no greetings or thank you after purchase. I start to wonder if this is the Starbucks' culture in the city of Chicago; while the bad news about poor service becomes a national news. I really hope that store and district managers do their job and train their employees to appreciate the brand customers. It is your daily responsibility to meet your customers' expectations. Waiting till the top management in Seattle decide to close all stores on May 29, 2018 is not enough. This store 1- should not refrain from making drinks at certain times 2- should not ask customers to leave 30 minutes before closing time 3- Sell fresh grab and go sandwiches and bakery, stop lying or being lazy when you can reach for fresh items instead of "we only sell what's on display!" 4- Greet your customers, thank them for their purchased, promote your store, hand them out their receipts; bear in your mind that your pay check depends on customers coming over to the store, otherwise choices are plenty and going to your competitors is one of them. Starbucks is Starbucks is Starbucks. NOT THIS ONE. It seems to me service at Starbucks has slipped over the years. There seems to be a bigger churn in employees. NOT AT THIS STARBUCKS. I go only in the morning hours before noon so I can't speak to afternoon service. However, the morning crew at this Starbucks is the best I've seen. They can turn a line of a dozen people disappear so proficiently. You will never catch any attitude. Special orders don't get you special looks. In summary, we all know Starbucks and what they have to offer. What we don't always know is Starbuck's service. Come to this store and find out how it's supposed to be done. Tell 'em Mo sent you. They'll laugh. That's my coffee name and it might even get your an extra shot of espresso.
